tional needs of all students, whether or not they qualify for pullout services (see Chapter 14). Educators can create more positive school-family relationships and serve the students who struggle with challenging family issues that may affect their ability to learn and behave at school (see Chapter 15)"--Preface. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2014 APA, all rights reserved).  aElectronic reproduction.bWashington, D.C. :cAmerican Psychological Association,d2014.nAvailable via World Wide Web.nAccess limited by licensing agreement.7s2014    dcunns  a21 44 57 0aChildren with disabilitiesxEducation. 0aChildren with disabilitiesxPsychological testing. 0aInterdisciplinary approach in education. 0aEducationxEvaluation. 0aNeeds assessment. 0aLearning, Psychology of. 0aLearningxPhysiological aspects. 0aBrain. 2aDisabled Childrenxeducation. 2aDisabled Childrenxpsychology. 2aInterdisciplinary Studies. 2aEducation. 2aNeeds Assessment. 2aPsychology, Educational. 2aBrain.403University of Alberta Accessuhttp://ovidsp.ovid.com/ovidweb.cgi?T=JS&NEWS=N&PAGE=toc&SEARCH=2014-08456.dd&LINKTYPE=asBody&D=psbk403MacEwan University Accessuhttp://search.ebscohost.com/direct.asp?db=pzh&jid=%22201408456%22&scope=site403Concordia University of Edmonton Accessuhttp://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=pzh&jid=201408456&site=ehost-live  hUAINzPSYCBOOKS  hUAINmCONCORDIAzPSYCBKSCON  hUAINmGR_MAC_INTzPSYCBKSGM  aInternet AccesswLCc1i6741090-1001lINTERNETmUAINTERNETrYsYtE-RESOURCEu11/21/2014xE-BOOKzPSYCBOOKS  aInternet AccesswLCc1i6741090-2001lINTERNETmCONCORDIArYsYtE-RESOURCEu11/21/2014xE-BOOKzPSYCBKSCON  aInternet AccesswLCc1i6741090-3001lINTERNETmGR_MAC_INTrYsYtE-RESOURCEu11/21/2014xE-BOOKzPSYCBKSGM01bhttp://viaf.org/viaf/37088227